 Claude McKay, Machariamoves through genres-psychoanalysis, fiction, anthropology, poetry-as well as regional geohistories across Africa and Afro-diaspora to map the centrality of sex, gender, desire, and eroticism to black freedom struggles. In lyrical, meditative prose, Macharia invigorates frottage as both metaphor and method with which to rethink diaspora by reading, and reading against, discomfort, vulnerability, and pleasure.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAfrican diaspora. 0aBlack peoplexSocial conditions. 0aBlacksxSocial conditions. 0aQueer theory. 0aSex. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Black Studies (Global).2bisacsh  aJamaica.  aKenya.  aKikuyu.  aaesthetics.  aanthropology.  acolonial modernity.  aderacination.  adesire.  aerotic.  aethnicity.  aethnography.  ahomosexual.  akinship.  amourning.  apoetry.  apunishment.  athinghood.  atouch.  aungendering.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z97831107227270 cprintz978147988114740uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479881147.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479802500423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479802500/original  a978-3-11-072272-7  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK